            ). Such huge risk premiums do not exist in overnight money markets since potential lenders choose simply to refrain from lending unsecured to institutions with any appreciable probability of default. Simply stated, markets are generally willing to lend unsecured only when the borrower has a relatively small probability of default. Thus two federal funds borrowers with slightly different, yet small, default risks will pay slightly different interest rates. A third borrower, which has a noticeably higher probability of default, will find it difficult to attract funds at any rate of interest.

In the empirical work to follow, one must make an assumption regarding how high risk premiums can go before quantity rationing begins. To provide guidance on this issue,figure 1graphs the distribution of interest rate premiums paid by the 164 institutions that borrowed in the funds market at least three out of every four days during the first half of 1998. A bank’s premium is defined as the volume‐weighted average of the difference between the interest rate paid less the daily effective funds rate.8As indicated, spreads cover a range of approximately 70 basis points. However, banks that are similar in terms of size and complexity typically have more similar average spreads. For example, the 33 banks identified in a recent Federal Reserve staff study as “large, complex banking organizations (LCBO)” (Federal Reserve1999, 28) typically pay spreads clustered within 20 basis points.9Further, banks that ultimately participated in the rescue of LTCM, on average, all paid between zero and 10 basis points above the effective rate for funds borrowed during the first half of 1998. Thus, if one of the LTCM banks was willing to pay interest at a rate much higher than 10 basis points above the effective rate, this could have the effect of signaling to the market that the institution was in serious difficulty. As an illustration, suppose that an LTCM bank might pay 25 basis points above its normal rate for overnight funds before withdrawing from the market. This additional risk premium compensates lenders for an increase in overnight default risk of one in 144,000 (calculated as
